AS Subject Content
Social Influence
Types of conformity: internalisation and compliance
Explanations for conformity: informational social influence (ISI) and normative social influence (NSI)
Variables affecting conformity: group size, unanimity, task difficulty — as investigated by Asch
Explanations for obedience: agentic state, legitimacy of authority
Situational variables affecting obedience: proximity, location (as investigated by Milgram), uniform
Dispositional explanation for obedience: the Authoritarian Personality
Resistance to social influence: social support, locus of control
Minority influence: consistency, commitment, flexibility
Memory
Multi-store model: sensory register, short-term memory (STM), long-term memory (LTM). Features: coding, capacity, duration
Working memory model: central executive, phonological loop, visuo-spatial sketchpad, episodic buffer. Features: coding, capacity
Explanations for forgetting: proactive and retroactive interference; retrieval failure due to absence of cues
Eyewitness testimony (EWT): leading questions, post-event discussion, anxiety; the cognitive interview
Attachment
Animal studies: Lorenz (imprinting), Harlow (contact comfort)
Explanations of attachment: learning theory; Bowlby's monotropic theory — critical period, internal working model
Ainsworth's Strange Situation: secure, insecure-avoidant, insecure-resistant attachment types
Cultural variations: van Ijzendoorn
Bowlby's maternal deprivation theory
Effects of institutionalisation: English and Romanian Adoptees project
Influence of early attachment on childhood and adult relationships; role of internal working model
Approaches in Psychology (AS)
Behaviourist approach: classical conditioning (Pavlov), operant conditioning (types of reinforcement, Skinner)
Social learning theory: imitation, identification, vicarious reinforcement, mediational processes (Bandura)
Cognitive approach: internal mental processes, role of schema, use of models
Biological approach: genotype, phenotype, evolution; biological structures and neurochemistry; cognitive neuroscience
Biopsychology (AS)
Divisions of the nervous system: central and peripheral (somatic and autonomic)
Structure and function of sensory, relay and motor neurons
Synaptic transmission: neurotransmitters, excitation, inhibition
Endocrine system: glands and hormones
Fight or flight response: role of adrenaline
Clinical Psychology and Mental Health
Definitions of mental health: deviation from ideal mental health, deviation from social/cultural norms, failure to function adequately, statistical infrequency
Characteristics of phobias, depression and OCD: behavioural, emotional, cognitive
Phobias — Behavioural approach: two-process model (classical + operant conditioning); systematic desensitisation (relaxation, hierarchy); flooding
Depression — Cognitive approach: Beck's negative triad; Ellis's ABC model; CBT (challenging irrational thoughts)
OCD — Biological approach: genetic and neural explanations; drug therapy
Research Methods (AS)
Methods:

Experimental method: laboratory, field, natural, quasi-experiments
Observational techniques: naturalistic/controlled, covert/overt, participant/non-participant
Self-report: questionnaires; structured and unstructured interviews
Correlations: relationship between co-variables; difference between correlations and experiments
Scientific Processes:

Aims and hypotheses (directional and non-directional)
Sampling: random, systematic, stratified, opportunity, volunteer; bias and generalisation
Pilot studies
Experimental designs: repeated measures, independent groups, matched pairs
Observational design: behavioural categories, event sampling, time sampling
Questionnaire construction: open and closed questions; interview design
Variables: IV, DV, extraneous; operationalisation
Control: random allocation, counterbalancing, randomisation, standardisation, control groups
Demand characteristics and investigator effects
Ethics: BPS code of ethics; ethical issues; dealing with ethical issues
Role of peer review
Implications of research for the economy
Data Handling and Analysis:

Quantitative and qualitative data
Primary and secondary data; meta-analysis
Descriptive statistics: mean, median, mode; range, standard deviation; percentages; correlations (positive, negative, zero)
Data presentation: graphs, tables, scattergrams, bar charts
Normal and skewed distributions
Introduction to statistical testing: the sign test (when to use, calculation)
A-Level Additional Content
All AS content is included in A-level. The following is content that is additional or extended for A-level only.

Approaches in Psychology (A-level additions)
Psychodynamic approach: role of the unconscious; structure of personality (Id, Ego, Superego); defence mechanisms (repression, denial, displacement); psychosexual stages
Humanistic Psychology: free will; self-actualisation; Maslow's hierarchy of needs; congruence; conditions of worth
Comparison of approaches
Biopsychology (A-level additions)
Studying the brain: fMRI scanning; EEGs and ERPs; post-mortem examinations
Localisation of function: motor, somatosensory, visual, auditory, language centres; Broca's area, Wernicke's area
Hemispheric lateralisation: split brain research
Plasticity and functional recovery after trauma
Research Methods (A-level additions)
Additional Methods:

Content analysis
Case studies
Additional Scientific Processes:

Reliability: test-retest, inter-observer; improving reliability
Validity: face, concurrent, ecological, temporal; measuring and improving validity
Features of science: objectivity, empirical method, replicability, falsifiability, theory construction, hypothesis testing, paradigms, paradigm shifts
Reporting investigations: abstract, introduction, method, results, discussion, referencing
Additional Data Handling:

Histograms
Correlation coefficients (analysis and interpretation)
Levels of measurement: nominal, ordinal, interval
Coding in content analysis
Inferential Testing:

Probability and significance: statistical tables, critical values, Type I and Type II errors
Factors affecting choice of test: level of measurement, experimental design
Tests to know when to use: Spearman's rho, Pearson's r, Wilcoxon, Mann-Whitney, related t-test, unrelated t-test, Chi-squared
A-Level Options (Paper 3)
Students choose ONE topic from each of the three option groups.

Option 1 (choose one)
Relationships
Factors affecting attraction: self-disclosure; physical attractiveness (matching hypothesis); filter theory (social demography, similarity in attitudes, complementarity)
Theories of romantic relationships: social exchange theory; equity theory; Rusbult's investment model (commitment, satisfaction, comparison with alternatives, investment)
Duck's phase model of breakdown: intra-psychic, dyadic, social, grave dressing phases
Online relationships: self-disclosure, deception, absence of gating
Parasocial relationships: levels of parasocial relationships; absorption addiction model; attachment theory explanation
Gender
Chromosomes and hormones: testosterone, oestrogen, oxytocin
Diversity in sex development: androgen insensitivity syndrome, Klinefelter's syndrome, Turner syndrome
Gender identities: binary, non-binary, gender fluid; Bem Sex Role Inventory
Biological explanations: chromosomes and hormones
Cognitive explanations: Kohlberg's theory (gender identity, stability, constancy); Martin & Halverson's gender schema theory
Social learning theory as applied to gender; influence of culture and media
Gender incongruence: biological and social/cultural explanations
Cognition and Development
Piaget's theory: schemas, assimilation, accommodation, equilibration; stages (object permanence, conservation, egocentrism, class inclusion)
Vygotsky's theory: zone of proximal development, scaffolding
Baillargeon: early infant abilities, knowledge of physical world, violation of expectation research
Social cognition: Selman's levels of perspective-taking; theory of mind; Sally-Anne study; mirror neuron system
Option 2 (choose one)
Schizophrenia
Symptoms: positive (hallucinations, delusions); negative (speech poverty, avolition)
Issues in diagnosis: co-morbidity, culture and gender bias, symptom overlap
Biological explanations: genetics, neural correlates, dopamine hypothesis
Psychological explanations: family dysfunction; cognitive explanations (dysfunctional thought processing)
Treatments: typical and atypical antipsychotics; CBT; family therapy
Interactionist approach: diathesis-stress model
Eating Behaviour
Food preferences: evolutionary explanation (neophobia, taste aversion); role of learning (social and cultural influences)
Neural and hormonal mechanisms: hypothalamus, ghrelin, leptin
Anorexia nervosa — Biological: genetic and neural explanations
Anorexia nervosa — Psychological: family systems theory (enmeshment, autonomy, control); social learning theory (modelling, reinforcement, media); cognitive theory (distortions, irrational beliefs)
Obesity — Biological: genetic and neural explanations
Obesity — Psychological: restraint theory, disinhibition, boundary model
Stress
Physiology of stress: general adaptation syndrome; HPA axis; sympathomedullary pathway; role of cortisol
Stress and illness: immunosuppression, cardiovascular disorders
Sources of stress: life changes, daily hassles, workplace stress (workload, control)
Measuring stress: SRRS, Hassles and Uplifts Scale; physiological measures (skin conductance response)
Individual differences: personality types A, B, C; hardiness (commitment, challenge, control)
Managing stress: drug therapy; stress inoculation therapy; biofeedback; gender differences in coping; social support (instrumental, emotional, esteem)
Option 3 (choose one)
Aggression
Neural and hormonal mechanisms: limbic system, serotonin, testosterone
Genetic factors: MAOA gene
Ethological explanation: innate releasing mechanisms, fixed action patterns
Evolutionary explanations of human aggression
Social psychological explanations: frustration-aggression hypothesis; social learning theory; de-individuation
Institutional aggression (prisons): dispositional and situational explanations
Media influences: computer games; desensitisation, disinhibition, cognitive priming
Forensic Psychology
Offender profiling: typology approach (organised/disorganised); data-driven approach (investigative psychology); geographical profiling
Biological explanations of offending: genetics, neural explanations
Psychological explanations: Eysenck's criminal personality; cognitive explanations (moral reasoning, cognitive distortions — hostile attribution bias, minimalisation); differential association theory
Dealing with offending: aims and effects of custodial sentencing; behaviour modification in custody; anger management; restorative justice
Addiction
Describing addiction: physical and psychological dependence, tolerance, withdrawal syndrome
Risk factors: genetic vulnerability, personality, social influences
Nicotine addiction: brain neurochemistry (dopamine); learning theory (cue reactivity)
Gambling addiction: learning theory (partial and variable reinforcement); cognitive theory (cognitive bias)
Reducing addiction: drug therapy; behavioural interventions (aversion therapy, covert sensitisation); CBT
Prochaska's six-stage model of behaviour change
Issues and Debates in Psychology (Compulsory A-level)
Gender and culture in Psychology: universality and bias; gender bias (androcentrism, alpha and beta bias); cultural bias (ethnocentrism, cultural relativism)
Free will and determinism: hard determinism, soft determinism; biological, environmental and psychic determinism; scientific emphasis on causal explanations
Nature-nurture debate: heredity vs environment; interactionist approach
Holism and reductionism: levels of explanation; biological reductionism; environmental (stimulus-response) reductionism
Idiographic and nomothetic approaches
Social sensitivity in psychological research
